b'' b'accounts of anti-armenian human right violations in azerbaijan part a' b'prelude to current events in nagorno-karabakh' b'' b'(part a of b'' b'+------------------------------------------------------------------+' b'| b'| "oh, yes, i just remembered. while they were raping me they b'| repeated quite frequently, "let the armenian women have babies b'| for us, muslim babies, let them bear azerbaijanis for the b'| struggle against the armenians." then they said, "those b'| muslims can carry on our holy cause. heroes!" they repeated b'| it very often." b'| b'+------------------------------------------------------------------+' b'' b'deposition of lyudmila grigorevna m.' b'' b'born b'teacher' b'sumgait secondary school no. b'secretary of the komsomol organization at school no. b'member of the sumgait city komsomol committee office' b'' b'resident at building 17/33b, apartment b'microdistrict no. b'sumgait [azerbaijan]' b'' b'[note: the events in kafan, used as a pretext to attack armenians in' b'azerbaijan are false, as verified by independent international human rights' b'organizations dd]' b'' b"i'm thinking about the price the sumgait armenians paid to be living in" b'armenia now. we paid for it in human casualties and crippled fates--the' b'price was too great! now, after the sumgait tragedy, we, the victims, divide' b'our lives into "before" and \'\'after." we talk like that: that was before the' b'war. like the people who went through world war ii and considered it a whole' b'epoch, a fate. no matter how many years go by, no matter how long we live,' b'it will never be forgotten. on the contrary, some of the moments become even' b'sharper: in our rage, in our sorrow, we saw everything differently, but now' b'. they say that you can see more with distance, and we can see those' b'inhuman events with more clarity now we more acutely perceive our' b'losses and everything that happened.' b'' b'nineteen eighty-eight was a leap year. everyone fears a leap year and wants it' b'to pass as quickly as possible. yet we never thought that that leap year would' b'be such a black one for every sumgait armenian: those who lost someone and' b"those who didn't." b'' b'that second to last day of winter was ordinary for our family, although you' b"could already smell danger in the air. but we didn't think that the danger was" b"near and possible, so we didn't take any steps to save ourselves. at least, as" b'my parents say, at least we should have done something to save the children.' b'my parents themselves are not that old, and years. but then they thought' b'that they had already lived enough, and did everything they could to save us.' b'' b'in our apartment the tragedy started on february around five in the' b'afternoon. i call it a tragedy, and i repeat: it was a tragedy even though all' b'our family survived. when i recall how they broke down our door my skin' b'crawls; even now, among armenians, among people who wish me only well, i feel' b"like it's all starting over again. i remember how that mob broke into our" b'apartment my parents were standing in the hall. my father had an axe in' b'his hands and had immediately locked both of the doors. our door was rarely' b"locked since friends and neighbors often dropped by. we're known as a" b'hospitable family, and we just never really thought about whether the people' b'who were coming to see us were azerbaijanis, jews, or russians. we had friends' b'of many nationalities, even a turkmen woman.' b'' b'my parents were in the hall, my father with an axe. i remember him telling my' b'mother, "run to the kitchen for a knife." but mother was detached, pale, as' b'though she had decided to sell her life a bit dearer. to be honest i never' b"expected it of her, she's afraid of getting shot and afraid of the dark. a" b'girlfriend was at the house that day, a russian girl, lyuda, and mamma said,' b'"no matter what happens, no matter what they do to us, you\'re not to come out' b'of the bedroom. we\'re going to tell them that we\'re alone in the apartment."' b'' b'we went into the bedroom. there were four of us. marina and the russian girl' b'crawled under the bed, and we covered them up with a rug, boxes of dishes, and' b'karina and i are standing there and looking at one another. the idea that' b'perhaps we were seeing each other for the last time flashed somewhere inside' b"me. i'm an emotional person and i express my emotions immediately. i wanted to" b'embrace her and kiss her, as though it were the last second. and maybe karina' b"was thinking the same thing, but she's quite reserved. we didn't have time to" b'say anything to each other because we immediately heard mamma raise a shout.' b'there was so much noise from the tramping of feet, from the shouting, and from' b"excited voices. i couldn't figure what was going on out there because the door" b'to the bedroom was only open a crack. but when mamma shouted the second time' b'karina ran out of the bedroom. i ran after her, i had wanted to hold her back,' b'but when she opened the door and ran out into the hall they saw us' b'immediately. the only thing i managed to do was close the door behind me, at' b'least so as to save marina and her friend. the mob was shouting, all of their' b'eyes were shining, all red, like from insomnia. at first about people burst' b"in, but later i was standing with my back to the door and couldn't see. they" b'came into the hall, into the kitchen, and dragged my father into the other' b"room. he didn't utter a word, he just raised the axe to hit them, but mamma" b'snatched the axe from behind and said, "tell them not to touch the children.' b'tell them they can do as they want with us, but not to harm the children." she' b'said this to father in armenian.' b'' b'there were azerbaijanis from armenia among the mob who broke in. they' b"understood armenian perfectly. the local azerbaijanis don't know armenian," b'they don\'t need to speak it. and one of them responded in armenian: "you and' b"your children both we're going to do the same thing to you and your" b'children that you armenians did in kafan. they killed our women, our girls,' b'our mothers, they cut their breasts off, and burned our houses and' b'so on and so forth, "and we came to do the same thing to you." this whole time' b'some of them are destroying the house and the others are shouting at us. they' b"were mostly young people, under at first there weren't any older people" b'among them. and all of their faces were unfamiliar. sumgait is a small town,' b"all the same, and we know a lot of people by their faces, especially me, i'm" b'a teacher.' b'' b'so they dragged my father into the other room. they twisted his arms and took' b"him in there, no they didn't take him in there, they dragged him in there," b'because he was already unable to walk. they closed the door to that room all' b"but a crack. we couldn't see what was happening to father, what they were" b'doing to him. then a young man, about years old, started to tear off' b'mamma\'s sarafan, and mamma shouted at him in azerbaijani: "i\'m old enough to' b'be your mother! what are you doing?!" he struck her. now he\'s being held,' b"mamma identified him. i hope he's convicted. then they went after karina," b"who's been talking to them like a komsomol leader, as though she were trying" b'to lead them down a different path, as they say, to influence their' b'consciousness. she told them that what they were doing was wrong, that they' b'mustn\'t do it. she said, "come on, let\'s straighten this out, without' b'emotions. what do you want? who are you? why did you come here? what did we' b'ever do to you?" someone tried to explain who they were and why they had come' b'into our home, but then the ones in the back--more of them kept coming and' b'coming--said, "what are you talking to, them for. you should kill them. we' b'came here to kill them."' b'' b'they pushed karina, struck her, and she fell down. they beat her, but she' b'didn\'t cry out. even when they tore her clothes off, she kept repeating, "what' b'did we do to you? what did we do to you?" and even later, when she came to,' b'she said, "mamma, what did we do to them? why did they do that to us?"' b'' b'that group was prepared, i know this because i noticed that some of them only' b'broke up furniture, and others only dealt with us. i remember that when they' b'were beating me, when they were tearing my clothes off, i felt neither pain' b'nor shame because my entire attention was riveted to karina. all i could do' b'was watch how much they beat her and how painful it was for her, and what they' b"did to her. that's why i felt no pain. later, when they carried karina off," b"they beat her savagely it's really amazing that she not only lived, but" b"didn't lose her mind she is very beautiful and they did everything they" b'could to destroy her beauty. mostly they beat her face, with their fists,' b'kicking her, using anything they could find.' b'' b"mamma, karina, and i were all in one room. and again i didn't feel any pain," b"just didn't feel any, no matter how much they beat me, no matter what they" b"did. then one of those creeps said that there wasn't enough room in the" b'apartment. they broke up the beds and the desk and moved everything into the' b'corners so there would be more room. then someone suggested, "let\'s take her' b'outside."' b'' b'those beasts were in heaven. they did what they would do every day if they' b"weren't afraid of the authorities. those were their true colors. at the time" b"i thought that in fact they would always behave that way if they weren't" b'afraid of what would happen to them.' b'' b'when they carried karina out and beat mamma-her face was completely covered' b"with blood--that's when i started to feel the pain. i blacked out several" b'times from the pain, but each moment that i had my eyes open it was as though' b"i were recording it all on film. i think i'm a kind person by nature, but i'm" b"vengeful, especially if someone is mean to me, and i don't deserve it. i hold" b'a grudge a long time if someone intentionally causes me pain. and every time' b"i would come to and see one of those animals on top of me, i'd remember them," b"and i'll remember them for the rest of my life, even though people tell me" b'"forget," you have to forget, you have to go on living.' b'' b'at some point i remember that they stood me up and told me something, and' b'despite the fact that i hurt all over--i had been beaten terribly--i found' b'the strength in myself to interfere with their tortures. i realized that i had' b'to do something: resist them or just let them kill me to bring my suffering' b'to an end. i pushed one of them away, he was a real horse. i remember now that' b"he's being held, too. as though they were all waiting for it, they seized me" b'and took me out onto the balcony. i had long hair, and it was stuck all over' b'me. one of the veranda shutters to the balcony was open, and i realized that' b'they planned to throw me out the window, because they had already picked me up' b'with their hands, i was up in the air. as though for the last time i took a' b'really deep breath and closed my eyes, and somehow braced myself inside, i' b'suddenly became cold, as though my heart had sunk into my feet. and suddenly' b"i felt myself flying. i couldn't figure out if i was really flying or if i" b"just imagined it. when i came to i thought now i'm going to smash on the" b"ground. and when it didn't happen i opened my eyes and realized that i was" b"still lying on the floor. and since i didn't scream, didn't beg them at all," b'they became all the more wild, like wolves. they started to trample me with' b'their feet. shoes with heels on them, and iron horseshoes, like they had spe-' b'cially put them on. then i lost consciousness.' b'' b'i came to a couple of times and waited for death, summoned it, beseeched it.' b"some people ask for good health, life, happiness, but at that moment i didn't" b'need any of those things. i was sure that none of us would survive, and i had' b"even forgotten about marina; and if none of us was alive, it wasn't worth" b'living.' b'' b'there was a moment when the pain was especially great. i withstood inhuman' b'pain, and realized that they were going to torment me for a long time to come' b'because i had showed myself to be so tenacious. i started to strangle myself,' b'and when i started to wheeze they realized that with my death i was going to' b'put an end to their pleasures, and they pulled my hands from my throat. the' b'person who injured and insulted me most painfully i remember him very well,' b'because he was the oldest in the group. he looked around i know that he' b'has four children and that he considers himself an ideal father and person,' b'one who would never do such a thing. something came over him then, you see,' b'even during the investigation he almost called me "daughter," he apologized,' b"although, of course, he knew that i'd never forgive him. something like that" b'i can never forgive. i have never injured anyone with my behavior, with my' b"words, or with my deeds, i have always put myself in the other person's shoes," b'but then, in a matter of hours, they trampled me entirely. i shall never' b'forget it.' b'' b'i wanted to do myself in then, because i had nothing to lose, because no one' b'could protect me. my father, who tried to do something against that hoard of' b"beasts by himself, could do nothing and wouldn't be able to do anything." b'i knew that i was even sure that he was no longer alive.' b'' b'and ira melkumian, my acquaintance i knew her and had been to see her family a' b"couple of times--her brother tried to save her and couldn't, so he tried to" b'kill her, his very own sister. he threw an axe at her to kill her and put an' b'end to her suffering. when they stripped her clothes off and carried her into' b"the other room, her brother knew what awaited her. i don't know which one it" b'was, edik or igor. both of them were in the room from which the axe was' b'thrown. but the axe hit one of the people carrying her and so they killed her' b'and made her death even more excruciating, maybe the most excruciating of all' b'the deaths of those days in sumgait. i heard about it all from the neighbor' b"from the melkumians' landing. his name is makhaddin, he knows my family a" b'little. he came to see how we had gotten settled in the new apartment in baku,' b"how we were feeling, and if we needed anything. he's a good person. he said," b'"you should praise god that you all survived. but what i saw with my own eyes,' b'i, a man, who has seen so many people die, who has lived a whole life, i," he' b'says, "nearly lost my mind that day. i had never seen the likes of it and' b'think i never shall again." the door to his apartment was open and he saw' b'everything. one of the brothers threw the axe, because they had already taken' b'the father and mother out of the apartment. igor, edik, and ira remained. he' b'saw ira, naked, being carried into the other room in the hands of six or seven' b'people. he told us about it and said he would never forget it. he heard the' b'brothers shouting something, inarticulate from pain, rage, and the fact that' b'they were powerless to do anything. but all the same they tried to' b'do something. the guy who got hit with the axe lived. i i' b'' b'after i had been unsuccessful at killing myself i saw them taking marina and' b"lyuda out of the bedroom. i was in such a state that i couldn't even" b'remember my sister\'s name. i wanted to cry "marina!" out to her, but could' b"not. i looked at her and knew that it was a familiar, dear face, but couldn't" b'for the life of me remember what her name was and who she was. and thus' b'i saved her, because when they were taking her out, she, as it turns out, had' b'told them that she had just been visiting and that she and lyuda were both' b"there by chance, that they weren't armenians. lyuda's a russian, you can tell" b'right away, and marina speaks azerbaijani wonderfully and she told them that' b"she was an azerbaijani. and i almost gave her away and doomed her. i'm glad" b'that at least marina came out of this all in good physical health b'although her spirit was murdered b'' b'at some point i came to and saw igor, igor agayev, my acquaintance, in that' b'mob. he lives in the neighboring building. for some reason i remembered his' b'name, maybe i sensed my defense in him. i called out to him in russian, "igor,' b'help!" but he turned away and went into the bedroom. just then they were' b'taking marina and lyuda out of the bedroom. igor said he knew marina and' b'lyuda, that marina in fact was azerbaijani, and he took both of them to the' b'neighbors.' b'' b'and the idea stole through me that maybe igor had led them to our apartment,' b'something like that, but if he was my friend, he was supposed to save me.' b'' b'then they were striking me very hard--we have an indian vase, a metal one,' b'they were hitting me on the back with it and i blacked out--they took me out' b'onto the balcony a second time to throw me out the window. they were already' b"sure that i was dead because i didn't react at all to the new blows. someone" b'said, "she\'s already dead, let\'s throw her out." when they carried me out onto' b'the balcony for the second time, when i was about to die the second time, i' b'heard someone say in azerbaijani: "don\'t kill her, i know her, she\'s a' b'teacher." i can still hear that voice ringing in my ears, but i can\'t remember' b"whose voice it was. it wasn't igor, because he speaks azerbaijani with an" b'accent: his mother is russian and they speak russian at home. he speaks' b'azerbaijani worse than our marina does. i remember when they carried me in and' b'threw me on the bed he came up to me, that person, and \ti having opened my' b'eyes, saw and recognized that person, but immediately passed out cold. i had' b"been beaten so much that i didn't have the strength to remember him. i only" b'remember that this person was older and he had a high position. unfortunately' b"i can't remember anything more." b'' b"what should i say about igor? he didn't treat me badly. i had heard a lot" b"about him, that he wasn't that good a person, that he sometimes drank too" b'much. once he boasted to me that he had served in afghanistan. he knew that' b'women usually like bravery in a man. especially if a man was in afghanistan,' b"if he was wounded, then it's about eighty percent sure that he will be treated" b'very sympathetically, with respect. later i found out that he had served in' b"ufa, and was injured, but that's not in afghanistan, of course. i found that" b'all out later.' b'' b'among the people who were in our apartment, my karina also saw the secretary' b"of the party organization. i don't know his last name, his first name is" b"najaf, he is an armenian-born azerbaijani. but later karina wasn't so sure," b'she was no longer a hundred percent sure that it was he she saw, and she' b'didn\'t want to endanger him. she said, "he was there," and a little while' b'later, "maybe they beat me so much that i am confusing him with someone else.' b'no, it seems like it was he." i am sure it was he because when he came to see' b'us the first time he said one thing, and the next time he said something' b"entirely different. the investigators haven't summoned him yet. he came to see" b'us in the khimik boarding house where we were living at the time. he brought' b'groceries and flowers, this was right before march 8th; he almost started' b"crying, he was so upset to see our condition. i don't know if he was putting" b'us on or not, but later, after we had told the investigator and they summoned' b"him to the procuracy, he said that he had been in baku, he wasn't in sumgait." b'the fact that he changed his testimony leads me to believe that karina is' b"right, that in fact it was he who was in our apartment. i don't know how the" b'investigators are now treating him. at one point i wondered and asked, and was' b"told that he had an alibi and was not in our apartment. couldn't he have gone" b"to baku and arranged an alibi? i'm not ruling out that possibility." b'' b'ill now return to our apartment. mamma had come to. you could say that she' b'bought them off with the gold father gave her when they were married: her' b"wedding band and her watch were gold. she bought her own and her husband's" b'lives with them. she gave the gold to a 14-year old boy. vadim vorobyev. a' b"russian boy, he speaks azerbaijani perfectly. he's an orphan who was raised by" b'his grandfather and who lives in sumgait on nizami street. he goes to a' b"special school, one for mentally handicapped children. but i'll say this--i'm" b'a teacher all the same and in a matter of minutes i can form an opinion--that' b"boy is not at all mentally handicapped. he's healthy, he can think just fine," b"and analyze, too policemen should be so lucky. and he's cunning, too." b'after that he went home and tore all of the pictures out of his photo album.' b'' b'he beat mamma and demanded gold, saying, "lady, if you give us all the gold' b'and money in your apartment we\'ll let you live." and mamma told them where' b'the gold was. he brought in the bag and opened it, shook out the contents, and' b'everyone who was in the apartment jumped on it, started knocking each other' b"over and taking the gold from one another. i'm surprised they didn't kill one" b'another right then.' b'' b'mamma was still in control of herself. she had been beaten up, her face was' b'black and blue from the blows, and her eyes were filled with blood, and she' b'ran into the other room. father was lying there, tied up, with a gag in his' b'mouth and a pillow over his face. there was a broken table on top of the pil-' b"low. mamma grabbed father and he couldn't walk; like me, he was half dead," b"halfway into the other world. he couldn't comprehend anything, couldn't see," b'and was covered with black and blue. mamma pulled the gag out of his mouth,' b'it was some sort of cloth, i think it was a slipcover from an armchair.' b'' b'the bandits were still in our apartment, even in the room mamma pulled father' b'out of, led him out of, carried him out of. we had two armchairs in that room,' b'a small magazine table, a couch, a television, and a screen. three people' b'were standing next to that screen, and into their shirts, their pants,' b'everywhere imaginable, they were shoving shot glasses and cups from the coffee' b'service--mamma saw them out of the corner of her eye. she said, "i was afraid' b'to turn around, i just seized father and started pulling him, but at the' b"threshold i couldn't hold him up, he fell down, and i picked him up again and" b'dragged him down the stairs to the neighbors\'." mamma remembered one of the' b'criminals, the one who had watched her with his face half-turned toward her,' b'out of one eye. she says, "i realized that my death would come from that' b'person. i looked him in the eyes and he recoiled from fear and went stealing."' b'later they caught that scoundrel. meanwhile, mamma grabbed father and left.' b'' b'i was alone. igor had taken marina away, mamma and father were gone, karina' b"was already outside, i didn't know what they were doing to her. i was left all" b'alone, and at that moment i became someone else, do you understand? even' b'though i knew that neither mother and father in the other room, nor marina and' b'lyuda under the bed could save me, all the same i somehow managed to hold out.' b'i went on fighting them, i bit someone, i remember, and i scratched another.' b'but when i was left alone i realized what kind of people they were, the ones' b'i had observed, the ones who beat karina, what kind of people they were, the' b'ones who beat me, that it was all unnecessary, that i was about to die and' b'that all of that would die with me.' b'' b'at some point i took heart when i saw the young man from the next building. i' b"didn't know his name, but we would greet one another when we met, we knew that" b'we were from the same microdistrict. when i saw him i said, "neighbor, is that' b'you?" in so doing i placed myself in great danger. he realized that if i lived' b"i would remember him. that's when he grabbed the axe. the axe that had been" b'taken from my father. i automatically fell to my knees and raised my hands to' b'take the blow of the axe, although at the time it would have been better if he' b'had struck me in the head with the axe and put me out of my misery. when he' b'started getting ready to wind back for the blow, someone came into the room.' b"the newcomer had such an impact on everyone that my neighbor's axe froze in" b'the air. everyone stood at attention for this guy, like soldiers in the' b'presence of a general. everyone waited for his word: continue the atrocities' b'or not. he said, "enough, let\'s go to the third entryway." in the third' b'entryway they killed uncle shurik, aleksandr gambarian. this confirms once' b'again that they had prepared in advance. almost all of them left with him, as' b'they went picking up pillows, blankets, whatever they needed, whatever they' b'found, all the way up to worn out slippers and one boot, someone else had' b'already taken the other.' b'' b"four people remained in the room, soldiers who didn't obey their general. they" b'had to have come recently, because other faces had flashed in front of me over' b'those to hours, but i had never seen those three. one of them, kuliyev (i' b'identified him later), a native of the sisian district of armenia, an' b'azerbaijani, had moved to azerbaijan a year before. he told me in armenian:' b'"sister, don\'t be afraid, i\'ll drive those three azerbaijanis out of here."' b'that\'s just what he said, "those azerbaijanis," as though he himself were not' b'azerbaijani, but some oth