knocked on the door, and he explained in azerbaijani. the neighbor woman' b'opened the door and immediately said, "i\'m an azerbaijani." he said, "i know.' b"let her sit at your place a while. don't open the door to anyone, no one knows" b'about this, i won\'t tell anyone. let her stay at your place." she says, "fine,' b'have her come in." i went in. she cried a bit and gave me some stockings, i' b'had gone entirely numb and was racked with nervous shudders. i burst into' b"tears. even though i was wearing marina's old fur coat, it's a short one, a" b'half-length, i was cold all the same. i asked, "do you know where my family' b'is, what happened to them?" she says, "no, i don\'t know anything. i\'m afraid' b"to go out of the apartment, now they're so wild that they don't look to see" b'who\'s azerbaijani and who\'s armenian." kuliyev left. ten minutes later my' b'neighbor says, "you know, lyuda, i don\'t want to lose my life because of you,' b'or my son and his wife. go stay with someone else." during the butchery in our' b'apartment one of the scum, a sadist, took my earring in his mouth--i had pearl' b'earrings on--and ripped it out, tearing the earlobe. the other earring was' b"still there. when i'm nervous i fix my hair constantly, and then, when i" b'touched my ear, i noticed that i had one earring on. i took it out and gave it' b'to her. she took the earring, but she led me out of the apartment.' b'' b"i went out and didn't know where to go. i heard someone going upstairs. i" b"don't know who it was but assumed it was them. with tremendous difficulty i" b'end up to our apartment, i wanted to die in my own home. i go into the' b'apartment and hear that they are coming up to our place, to the fifth floor.' b'i had to do something. i went into the bedroom where marina and lyuda had' b'hidden and saw that the bed was overturned. instead of hiding i squatted near' b'some broken christmas ornaments, found an unbroken one, and started sobbing.' b'then they came in. someone said that there were still some things to take. i' b'think that someone pushed me under the bed. i lay on the floor, and there were' b'broken ornaments on it, under my head and legs. i got all cut up, but i lay' b'there without moving. my heart was beating so hard it seemed the whole town' b"could hear it. there were no lights on. maybe that's what saved me. they were" b'burning matches, and toward the end they brought in a candle. they started' b"picking out the clothes that could still be worn. they took father's sport" b'jacket and a bedspread, the end of which was under my head. they pulled on the' b'one end, and it felt like they were pulling my hair out. i almost cried out.' b"and again i realized i wasn't getting out of there alive, and i started to" b'strangle myself again. i took my throat in one hand, and pressed the other on' b'my mouth, so as not to wheeze, so that i would die and they would only find me' b'afterward. they were throwing the burned matches under the bed, and i got' b"burned, but i withstood it. something inside of me held on, someone's hand was" b"protecting me to the end. i knew that i was going to die, but i didn't know" b'how. i knew that if i survived i would walk out of that apartment, but if' b'i found out that one of my family had died, i would die for sure, because i' b"had never been so close to death and couldn't imagine how you could go on" b'living without your mother or father, or without your sister. marina, i' b"thought, was still alive: she went to lyuda's place or someone is hiding her." b"i tried to think that igor wouldn't let them be killed. he served in" b'afghanistan, he should protect her.' b'' b'while i was strangling myself i said my good-byes to everyone. and then i' b'thought, how could marina survive alone. if they killed all of us, how would' b'she live all by herself? there were six people in the room. they talked among' b'themselves and smoked. one talked about his daughter, saying that there was no' b"children's footwear in our apartment that he could take for his daughter." b'another said that he liked the apartment--recently we had done a really good' b'job fixing everything up--and that he would live there after everything was' b'all over. they started to argue. a third one says, "how come you get it? i' b"have four children, and there are three rooms here, that's just what i need." b'all these years i\'ve been living in god-awful places." another one says,' b'"neither of you gets it. we\'ll set fire to it and leave." then someone said' b'that azerbaijanis live right next door, the fire could move over to their' b"place. and they, to my good fortune, didn't set fire to the apartment, and" b'left.' b'' b'oh, yes, i just remembered. while they were raping me they repeated quite' b'frequently, "let the armenian women have babies for us, muslim babies, let' b'them bear azerbaijanis for the struggle against the armenians." then they' b'said, "those muslims can carry on our holy cause. heroes!" they repeated it' b'very often.' b'' b'- reference for b'' b'[1] _the sumgait tragedy; pogroms against armenians in soviet azerbaijan,' b'volume i, eyewitness accounts_, edited by samuel shahmuradian, forward by' b'yelena bonner, published by aristide d. caratzas, ny, pages b'' b'' b'--' b"s.d.p.a. center for regional studies the armenian border, when we can't" b'p.o. box even explain b'cambridge, ma turkish mp, march 